segments.text: Is there any price put on research, for example, for tenure or for any of the other?
What is put on, I think, is imposed by a professor's own colleagues.
Any decisions about tenure or promotion are initiated in the department.
I think that's where the greatest pressure is put on.
I'm sure that if we sent regularly professors who did not publish that the College of Education, Dean Corrigan in particular, would be very, very unhappy about it.
But he's also taken the position that research is not the only way that a professor can excel, teaching is service.
And so a minimum amount of research, publication, coupled with a great amount of service are great attention to students.
And for us, the biggest part of teaching is not
standing in the classroom at 25 or 30, the greatest part is doctoral advisement.
And that also can play a role.
And I think it's been very successful in selling this to the university.
And yet, as I said, I don't think there ever has been a lot of pressure to research.
Research, in fact, has expanded since when I first came within the department.
But I think part of the...
research has never been, the pressure has not been great, is that perhaps engineering is sort of the prototype of what A&M is all about, decreasingly so.
Engineering, professors have never done a lot of research.
In spite of the image, it's only a minority of their professors
really been engaged in research.
And a lot of them have done a lot of service.
They've done small research projects.
Not really any, the great majority are not consequential things.
And they don't publish much at all.
So I think that has taken some of the pressure off.
OK. That takes us in.
And I would like to just see if you have any

either a highlight of your 10 years of A&M, something that stands out in your mind as something very special, or something about what you feel maybe in these 10 years has been your greatest contribution, and just an insight or an anecdote or some observation that you've made that would be, again, something that comes from just your own inner feelings and wouldn't be documented anywhere, just your own personal.
Well, yeah.
No.

I guess I'll be egocentric in my response, too, because the thing of which I'm most proud of and I feel best about is the obviously powerful feeling of family and collegiality that I think we've developed in the Department of Educational Administration.
It's something I've worked at.
I haven't been alone in it, but the response has been great.

And I don't think we've ever had, well, I don't know of any other department anywhere that has the same amount of collegiality, not only among professors, but among the graduate students, between student professors, and even to include the secretary of the classified staff.
And I feel very good about that and the way that that has evolved and is evolving.
Yeah, I thought everybody was the same.
Not having been exposed to the other ones and having felt that camaraderie in the group itself there, I thought that was part of it.
But that's good.
Is there something you've done that's special that has created that?
You said you work hard at it.
What did you do to turn it around if it wasn't there?
Well, a couple of things.
Formal things is I have really stressed and continue to stress the fact that professors ought not to be in their own offices following only their own agendas, developing only their own excellence.
But they also ought to be working on joint projects.
Several professors ought to be working on the same project.
They need to share.
They need to involve each other.
I've also, in pursuit of that, I've encouraged particular professors, two or three, to work together on the same thing or to bring another professor in.
I've also explicitly stated that I would like to see more involvement with the students in researching on the really interesting things, more collegiality, and more chance for dialogue.
I certainly haven't done this myself, but certainly there have been other people, any other professors who have been interested in this, and my main contribution there has been to encourage them.
Stan Carpenter has come to build up the collegiology he has among the students involved in higher education.
He needs to take primary credit for that.
The only credit I feel is
that I can take part in the green light and encourage them to do it.
I'll also stress another thing that this department had in that, well, it was a very similar thing.
And I've never issued a statement on it, a formal statement, that this is what had to be done.
Excuse me.
Oh, OK.
Thanks.
Thank you, Alonzo.
That's OK.
I've encouraged them to use their graduate assistants in really on the important things of the department, their research, their writing, et cetera, which they've done.
And I've discouraged them.
I said, don't give the graduate assistant all the experience of just doing formalistic gopher kinds of stuff.
And I would say, when I came, that was probably the norm.
requirements for the graduate assistant.
And I think that's turned around very nicely.
And I think these graduate assistants aren't getting paid enough in dollars.
They ought to be getting something a lot more out of it than just the money.
Very good.
And in closing, is there anything that you would like to share?
Some little incident or anecdote, anything that

that, again, stands out as something that you feel pretty good about that has happened while you've been there, in or out of the department or in a relationship with other students, a particular student or a particular event or something that...
I would say personally, you know, I was just sitting out from the department to be expanded, I guess, both to my interactions with students.
Also, I think it also could be expanded to

college generally, certainly I think one of the most rewarding things, maybe the most rewarding thing since I've been here is the tremendous number of good doctoral students I've been privileged to work with and some really good research that they've done and gotten to know them and to understand them and to help them along the way.
The second thing that was in that same vein is that I think
It's just been a real joy, just a very refreshing experience to have Dean Corrigan here just to open up the possibilities and encourage in so many areas.
I cannot imagine another individual whom we could have selected for the position that would have done a better job.
And speaking, I guess, to my own deficits as a
As in personnel selection, of the five we looked at, he wasn't my top choice of the five.
But I'm sure, in retrospect, that we could have done it better.
He would be now.
There's no question about it.
You feel that, perhaps, he was just the right person at the right time in the right place.
Yes.
And I think it's worked out beautifully.
And because the college has grown so much, I guess he has a hard time himself, just like you said, between departments and keeping a close contact.
But I guess he does it for you all as department heads to transmit this feeling.
He does.
And I guess in some ways, I would say, I think Oregon is looking as an administrator rather than as a leader.
Probably some of them are sloppy administrators.
He's not a very tidy administrator.
Uh, leaves a lot of loose ends, but that, maybe that's good.
Maybe that's good.
That's his style.
Yeah, that's his style, and I think that that's brought in, enabled some of the graffiti to get back in that we, that we've been lacking.
A certain amount of that is needed in the institution of higher education.

So the College of Education, you feel, is alive and well, and in spite of all of the things that we're facing, which a lot of the changes that are coming about through the legislature and all will not have an adverse effect, if anything?
Well, they may have an adverse effect, but it's not going to slow it down.
It's going to have to be some major internal change in ways in order for it to be set back down.
External factors are not going to turn it around now.
Dr. Owens, I really appreciate you sharing all of these perceptions of the past and the present and the future.
And certainly you have contributed a great deal to the growth, especially of the administration department
And I think the fact that the service is so prevalent in the department that you chair is a source of satisfaction because that's what education is, is going after and serving.
So I appreciate it, and I will visit with you further.
Okay, great.
